#: ../../../reference/random/generated/numpy.random.Generator.normal.rst:4
msgid "numpy.random.Generator.normal"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/generated/numpy.random.Generator.normal.rst:8
msgid "method"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:2
msgid "Draw random samples from a normal (Gaussian) distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:4
msgid ""
"The probability density function of the normal distribution, first derived "
"by De Moivre and 200 years later by both Gauss and Laplace independently "
"[R1536f9c044a3-2]_, is often called the bell curve because of its "
"characteristic shape (see the example below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:9
msgid ""
"The normal distributions occurs often in nature.  For example, it describes "
"the commonly occurring distribution of samples influenced by a large number "
"of tiny, random disturbances, each with its own unique distribution "
"[R1536f9c044a3-2]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:0
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:17
msgid "**loc**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:-1
msgid "float or array_like of floats"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:17
msgid "Mean (\"centre\") of the distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:21
msgid "**scale**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:20
msgid ""
"Standard deviation (spread or \"width\") of the distribution. Must be non-"
"negative."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:29
msgid "**size**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:-1
msgid "int or tuple of ints, optional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:24
msgid ""
"Output shape.  If the given shape is, e.g., ``(m, n, k)``, then ``m * n * "
"k`` samples are drawn.  If size is ``None`` (default), a single value is "
"returned if ``loc`` and ``scale`` are both scalars. Otherwise, ``np."
"broadcast(loc, scale).size`` samples are drawn."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:0
msgid "Returns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:40
msgid "**out**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:-1
msgid "ndarray or scalar"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:34
msgid "Drawn samples from the parameterized normal distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:45
msgid ":obj:`scipy.stats.norm`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:46
msgid ""
"probability density function, distribution or cumulative density function, "
"etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:50
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:51
msgid "The probability density for the Gaussian distribution is"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:53
msgid ""
"p(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{ 2 \\pi \\sigma^2 }}\n"
"e^{ - \\frac{ (x - \\mu)^2 } {2 \\sigma^2} },\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:56
msgid ""
"where :math:`\\mu` is the mean and :math:`\\sigma` the standard deviation. "
"The square of the standard deviation, :math:`\\sigma^2`, is called the "
"variance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:60
msgid ""
"The function has its peak at the mean, and its \"spread\" increases with the "
"standard deviation (the function reaches 0.607 times its maximum at :math:`x "
"+ \\sigma` and :math:`x - \\sigma` [R1536f9c044a3-2]_).  This implies that :"
"meth:`normal` is more likely to return samples lying close to the mean, "
"rather than those far away."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:67
msgid "References"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.normal:68
